<subSubSection id="C37F6528FFA35663FC8120856942878B" pageId="1" pageNumber="474" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BDA36A3FFA35663FC8120856942878B" blockId="1.[811,1452,1213,1717]" pageId="1" pageNumber="474">
<emphasis id="B911EAB1FFA35663FC8120856FA985EB" bold="true" box="[813,1020,1213,1237]" pageId="1" pageNumber="474">Revised diagnosis.</emphasis>
The discovery of 
<taxonomicName id="4C654D20FFA35663FB172086694D85EB" authority="Tanasevitch, 2020" authorityName="Tanasevitch" authorityYear="2020" box="[1211,1304,1213,1237]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Ummeliata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="474" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jambi" status="new species">
<emphasis id="B911EAB1FFA35663FB172086694D85EB" box="[1211,1304,1213,1237]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="474">U. jambi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A22257CAFFA35663FA89208669FD85EB" box="[1317,1448,1213,1237]" pageId="1" pageNumber="474" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
, warrants the diagnosis of the genus as given by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF44B52FFA35663FAB220E569F285CB" author="Eskov" box="[1310,1447,1245,1269]" firstAuthor="Eskov" pageId="1" pageNumber="474" pagination="1743 - 1746" refId="ref3366" refString="Eskov KY (1980) Taxonomic notes on spiders of the genus Hummelia (Aranei, Linyphiidae) with a description of a new species. Zoologicheskii Zhurnal, 59: 1743 - 1746." type="journal article" year="1980">Eskov (1980</bibRefCitation>
, as 
<taxonomicName id="4C654D20FFA35663FCE520C56FED842B" box="[841,952,1277,1301]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Hummelia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="474" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B911EAB1FFA35663FCE520C56FED842B" box="[841,952,1277,1301]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="474">Hummelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) to be refined. Species of this genus are smallsized (total length about 2.0–3.0) with a modified carapace. The formula of chaetotaxy is 2.2.1.1, metatarsi I–IV each with a trichobothrium. The male palp is characterised by the presence of a large convector, a relatively long and coiled embolus, and a totally or strongly reduced radix in the embolic division. By having a large body, the chaeto- and trichobothriotaxy patterns, the modified male carapace, the long and coiled embolus, and the strongly reduced radix, 
<taxonomicName id="4C654D20FFA35663FC8122256FF7870B" authorityName="Strand" authorityYear="1942" box="[813,930,1565,1589]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Ummeliata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="474" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B911EAB1FFA35663FC8122256FF7870B" box="[813,930,1565,1589]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="474">Ummeliata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C654D20FFA35663FBBE222669FD870B" authority="Wunderlich &amp; Song, 1995" authorityName="Wunderlich &amp; Song" authorityYear="1995" box="[1042,1448,1565,1589]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Nasoonaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="474" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B911EAB1FFA35663FBBE222668DB870B" box="[1042,1166,1566,1589]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="474">Nasoonaria</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFF44B52FFA35663FB39222569FD870B" author="Wunderlich &amp; Song" box="[1173,1448,1565,1589]" firstAuthor="Wunderlich" pageId="1" pageNumber="474" pagination="343 - 351" refId="ref4146" refString="Wunderlich J &amp; Song DX (1995) Four new spider species of the families Anapidae, Linyphiidae and Nesticidae from a tropical rain forest area of SW-China. Beitrage zur Araneologie, 4: 343 - 351." type="journal article" year="1995">Wunderlich &amp; Song, 1995</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName id="4C654D20FFA35663FC3222056840876B" authorityName="Strand" authorityYear="1942" box="[926,1045,1597,1621]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Ummeliata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="474" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B911EAB1FFA35663FC3222056840876B" box="[926,1045,1597,1621]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="474">Ummeliata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clearly differs from the latter by the absence of a convector in the embolic division, as well as by the poorly developed distal suprategular apophysis, which is hypertrophied in the males of 
<taxonomicName id="4C654D20FFA35663FB3822A66945878B" authorityName="Wunderlich &amp; Song" authorityYear="1995" box="[1172,1296,1694,1717]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Nasoonaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="474" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B911EAB1FFA35663FB3822A66945878B" box="[1172,1296,1694,1717]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="474">Nasoonaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37F6528FFA35663FC8122E5697586CB" pageId="1" pageNumber="474" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BDA36A3FFA35663FC8122E5697586CB" blockId="1.[811,1452,1757,2038]" pageId="1" pageNumber="474">
<emphasis id="B911EAB1FFA35663FC8122E5697287CB" bold="true" box="[813,1319,1757,1781]" pageId="1" pageNumber="474">Species included and their distributions.</emphasis>
The genus includes nine species distributed in the southeastern parts of the Palearctic (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF44B52FFA35663FC6B232568A1860B" author="World Spider Catalog" box="[967,1268,1821,1845]" firstAuthor="World Spider Catalog" pageId="1" pageNumber="474" refId="ref4113" refString="World Spider Catalog (2020) World Spider Catalog. Version 21.0. Natural History Museum Bern. http: // wsc. nmbe. ch (Accessed 05 April 2020)." type="url" year="2020">World Spider Catalog, 2020</bibRefCitation>
), but one species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C654D20FFA35663FC872306695C866B" authority="(Bosenberg &amp; Strand, 1906)" baseAuthorityName="Bosenberg &amp; Strand" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[811,1289,1853,1877]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Ummeliata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="474" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insecticeps">
<emphasis id="B911EAB1FFA35663FC8723066F91866B" box="[811,964,1854,1877]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="474">U. insecticeps</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFF44B52FFA35663FC7A23056954866B" author="Bosenberg &amp; Strand" box="[982,1281,1853,1877]" firstAuthor="Bosenberg" pageId="1" pageNumber="474" pagination="93 - 422" refId="ref3253" refString="Bosenberg W &amp; Strand E (1906) Japanische Spinnen. Abhandlungen der Senckenbergischen Naturforschenden Gesellschaft, 30: 93 - 422." type="journal article" year="1906">Bösenberg &amp; Strand, 1906</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, has also been recorded from the Oriental Region: northern 
<collectingCountry id="F3727633FFA35663FAB32365692E864B" box="[1311,1403,1885,1909]" name="Vietnam" pageId="1" pageNumber="474">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFF44B52FFA35663FA2023656FF986AB" author="Tu &amp; Li" firstAuthor="Tu" pageId="1" pageNumber="474" pagination="419 - 433" refId="ref4080" refString="Tu LH &amp; Li SQ (2004) A preliminary study of erigonine spiders (Linyphiidae: Erigoninae) from Vietnam. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 52: 419 - 433." type="journal article" year="2004">Tu &amp; Li, 2004</bibRefCitation>
), and is here reported from northern 
<collectingCountry id="F3727633FFA35663FAE42346692986AB" box="[1352,1404,1918,1941]" name="Laos" pageId="1" pageNumber="474">Laos</collectingCountry>
and northern 
<collectingCountry id="F3727633FFA35663FC2323A56F93868B" box="[911,966,1949,1973]" name="India" pageId="1" pageNumber="474">India</collectingCountry>
for the first time, as shown below. The new species, described below, is the second representative of the genus to be registered in the Oriental Region.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
